===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|ang|linke}}, probably from {{der|en|non|*hlenkr}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*hlankaz}}. Used in English since the 14th century. See more at {{m|en|lank}}, {{m|en|flank}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[connection]] between [[place]]s, [[people]], [[event]]s, [[thing]]s, or [[idea]]s.
#: ''The mayor’s assistant serves as the '''link''' to the media.''
#* Cowper
#*: The '''link''' of brotherhood, by which / One common Maker bound me to the kind.
#* Gascoigne
#*: And so by double '''links''' enchained themselves in lover's life.
# One element of a [[chain]] or other connected series.
#: ''The third '''link''' of the silver chain needs to be resoldered.''
#: ''The weakest '''link'''.''
# {{abbreviation of|hyperlink|lang=en}}
#: ''The '''link''' on the page points to the sports scores.''
# {{label|en|computing}} The connection between [[bus]]es or systems.
#: ''A by-N-'''link''' is composed of N lanes.''
# {{label|en|mathematics}} A [[space]] [[comprise|comprising]] one or more [[disjoint]] [[knot]]s.
# {{label|en|Sussex}} a thin wild bank of land splitting two cultivated patches and often linking two hills.
#* '''2008''', Richard John King, ''A Handbook for Travellers in Kent and Sussex''
#*: They used formerly to live in caves or huts dug into the side of a bank or "'''link'''," and lined with heath or straw.
# {{label|en|figurative}} a

===Etymology 2===
Plausibly a modification of {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|linchinus||candle}}, an alteration of {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|lynchinus}}, itself from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|λύχνος||lamp}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{label|en|obsolete}} A [[torch]], used to light dark streets.
#* '''1854''', Dickens, ''Hard Times'', Chapter 7:
#*: You were coming out of the Italian Opera, ma’am, in white satin and jewels, a blaze of splendour, when I hadn’t a penny to buy a '''link''' to light you.’
#* '''1883''', Robert Louis Stevenson, ''Treasure Island''
#*: "Give me a loan of the '''link''', Dick."
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}}

